         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>Derived from one of four columns  adapted to carry statues, probably of the tetrarchs
                    (cf. the  four columns described by P. Lacau, <title level="j">Annales du Service des Antiquités de l'égypt</title> XXXIV (1934) 17f.) 
                    and intended as frontier markers (for a parallel see  D. Schlumberger, <title level="j">Syria</title> XX (1939) 43f., which suggests that the imperial names would be in the dative case. </p>
            <p> On the site see Goodchild. 94f.</p>
            <p> The language originally suggested that this was a monument of Tripolitania; but it is now known that Latin was common in official texts of early 
                IV century Ptolemais, so that there is no strong reason against associating it with the much nearer Cyrenaica. </p>
            <p> The text was plastered over in antiquity, presumably in a post-Diocletianic reorganisation of the monument; cf on <ref type="inscription">B00200</ref>.</p>
         </div>
         
